{"Body": "<p>An Eaglais is consp&oacute;id&iacute; in &Eacute;irinn i l&aacute;thair na huaire n&aacute; &ldquo;The Church of Dermotology.&rdquo; (N&oacute; an dara Eaglais is consp&oacute;id&iacute; ar a laghad.) Cheapf&aacute; gur cultas reiligi&uacute;nach eile at&aacute; ann ar dt&uacute;s. N&oacute; gr&iacute;os cnis! Ach n&iacute; mar sin at&aacute; an sc&eacute;al&hellip;</p>\n<p>Buna&iacute;odh &ldquo;The Church of Dermotology&rdquo; mar fhreagra ar an dl&iacute; nua in &eacute;adan an diamhasla a th&aacute;inig i bhfeidhm ar an gc&eacute;ad l&aacute; d&rsquo;&Eacute;an&aacute;ir 2010 mar chuid den Acht Um Chl&uacute;mhilleadh. Dar leis an dl&iacute; nua seo, gearrfar p&iacute;on&oacute;s nach m&oacute; n&aacute; &euro;25,000 ar &eacute;inne a fhaightear ciontach as diamhasla. T&aacute; go leor cur agus c&uacute;iteamh ann faoin dl&iacute; seo agus an bac a chuirfidh s&eacute; ar shaoirse cainte.</p>\n<p>Bhunaigh Michael Nugent, Uachtar&aacute;n Atheist Ireland, &ldquo;The Church of Dermotology&rdquo; in &oacute;m&oacute;s an Aire Dl&iacute; is Cirt, Dermot Ahern leis an dl&iacute; a th&aacute;st&aacute;il. (Imeartas focal d&aacute;r nd&oacute;igh at&aacute; in ainm na hEaglaise ar ainm Dermot Ahern agus ar an &ldquo;Church of Scientology&rdquo;). De r&eacute;ir an dl&iacute; nua seo, is &eacute;ard at&aacute; i &ldquo;ndiamhasla&rdquo; n&aacute; r&aacute;itis n&oacute; foilseach&aacute;in a mhasla&iacute;onn aon nithe at&aacute; beannaithe ag aon chreideamh ar bith agus a spreagann uaf&aacute;s d&rsquo;aon ghn&oacute; i &ldquo;l&iacute;on substainti&uacute;il&rdquo; de lucht lean&uacute;na an chreidimh &uacute;d. Ach t&aacute; an s&aacute;inmhini&uacute; seo chomh doil&eacute;ir gur deacair a shamhl&uacute; conas gur f&eacute;idir an reachta&iacute;ocht a chur in &eacute;ifeacht. Cad is br&iacute; le &ldquo;l&iacute;on substainti&uacute;il?&rdquo; An &eacute; sin 99% de leant&oacute;ir&iacute; an chreidimh i gceist? N&oacute; an leor aon trian d&oacute;ibh? Ach nach bhf&eacute;adfa&iacute; diamhasla a chur i leith daoine ar n&oacute;s Arthur Mathews and Graham Linehan, scr&iacute;obhneoir&iacute; Father Ted, an cl&aacute;r teilif&iacute;se is c&aacute;illi&uacute;la d&aacute;r rinneadh in &Eacute;irinn riamh?</p>\n<p>Is &iacute; an phr&iacute;omhchreidi&uacute;nt at&aacute; ag &ldquo;The Church of Dermotology&rdquo; n&aacute; gur sheol Dia Dermot Ahern go h&Eacute;irinn chun an t&iacute;r a sh&aacute;bh&aacute;il &oacute; &ldquo;smaoineamh r&eacute;as&uacute;nach.&rdquo; T&aacute; fobhrist&iacute; le ceannach fi&uacute; ar a bhfuil siombal na hEaglaise (The Star of Dermot) orthu. Creidtear go diongbh&aacute;ilte go gcosna&iacute;onn na fobhrist&iacute; &ldquo;dra&iacute;ocht&uacute;la&rdquo; seo an duine at&aacute; &aacute; gcaitheamh &oacute; thine agus &oacute; phil&eacute;ir! Creidtear chomh maith gur ionann wafers uachtar reoite agus corp Dermot Ahern. Mar sin, is geall le diamhasla wafers uacthar reoite a ithe, dar leis an Eaglais. Anuas ar seo, t&aacute; an eagra&iacute;ocht a&rsquo; r&aacute; gur diamhasla thar na bearta at&aacute; ann, dar leo, aon phicti&uacute;ir a fhoilsi&uacute; d&aacute; nDia, Dermot Ahern, agus t&aacute; siad toilteanach an dl&iacute; a chur ar &eacute;inne a dh&eacute;anann a l&eacute;ith&eacute;id le teorainn an dl&iacute; nua a th&aacute;st&aacute;il. A l&eacute;ith&eacute;id de sheaf&oacute;id? B&rsquo;fh&eacute;idir &eacute;, ach caithfear a adhmh&aacute;il go bhfuil ag &eacute;ir&iacute; go seoigh leis an eagra&iacute;ocht aird a tharraingt ar c&eacute; chomh d&aacute;ir&iacute;re is at&aacute; an reachta&iacute;ocht seo.</p>\n<p>N&iacute; miste s&uacute;il a leagan ar impleachta&iacute; an dl&iacute; seo ar th&iacute;ortha eile. Is cos&uacute;il go bhfuil an dl&iacute; ag cur breosla ar teannas agus antoisceachas domhanda. Sna N&aacute;isi&uacute;in Aontaithe, bhain an Phacast&aacute;in &uacute;s&aacute;id as sampla na h&Eacute;ireann cheana f&eacute;in mar thaca&iacute;ocht lena dtuairim gur ch&oacute;ir dl&iacute; mar seo a chur i bhfeidhm ar bonn idirn&aacute;isi&uacute;nta.</p>\n<p>In &Eacute;irinn, t&aacute; baol ann go ngr&iacute;osfaidh an dl&iacute; seo daoine radacacha le seasamh antoisceach a ghlacadh. An g&aacute; do chl&aacute;ir ar n&oacute;s That&rsquo;s All We&rsquo;ve Time For agus The Savage Eye aire a thabhairt? N&oacute; an gcaithfidh scr&iacute;obhneoir&iacute; scripte do shobalchl&aacute;ir abh&aacute;ir chonsp&oacute;ideacha a ch&aacute;ineann an Eaglais a sheachaint? Ach n&rsquo;fheadar c&eacute;n f&aacute;th go mbeadh &eacute;inne ag c&aacute;ineadh na hEaglaise&hellip;.</p>\n<p>N&iacute; cioncheap &uacute;rnua &eacute; an dl&iacute; in &eacute;adan an diamhasla- ba chuid den Bhunreacht &eacute; i 1937. Ach is d&oacute;igh go bhfuil athr&uacute; meoin tagtha ar mhuintir na h&Eacute;ireann &oacute; shin. Ior&oacute;nta b&rsquo;fh&eacute;idir gur scr&iacute;obhadh dl&iacute; an diamhasla sa bhliain ch&eacute;anna in&aacute;r th&aacute;inig scannail agus uaf&aacute;is na hEaglaise Chaitlic&iacute; chun l&eacute;argais. &nbsp;Cinnte, n&iacute; f&eacute;idir a sh&eacute;anadh ach go raibh forl&aacute;mhas ag an Eaglais ar an st&aacute;it nuair a cumadh Bunreacht na h&Eacute;ireann. Ach n&iacute; mar sin at&aacute; s&eacute; a thuilleadh. T&aacute; &aacute;r saoirse cainte &aacute; creimeadh ag reacta&iacute;ocht nua seo. An nglacfaimid le dl&iacute; mar seo sa tsocha&iacute; iolra&iacute;och at&aacute; againn in &Eacute;irinn inniu.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Church of Dermotology- Ireland&rsquo;s most controversial Church at the moment. (Or the second most controversial at the least.) At first you&rsquo;d imagine it was just another religious cult. Or a skin condition! But it isn&rsquo;t quite like that&hellip;</p>\n<p>The Church of Dermotology was set up in response to the new law against blasphemy that was introduced on the 1st January 2010 as part of the Defamation Act. According to this new law, anyone found guilty of blasphemy will be fined up to &euro;25,000. There has been great debate over the law and its implications on freedom of speech.</p>\n<p>Michael Nugent, the President of Atheist Ireland set up the Church in honor of the Dermot Ahern, the Minister of Justice, in order &nbsp;to test the blasphemy law. (The name of the Church is of course a clever pun on the Minister&rsquo;s Name and &lsquo;&rsquo;The Church if Scientology.&rsquo;&rsquo;) According to the law, blasphemy is defined as any statement or publication that is insulting in relation to matters held sacred by any religion and that causes deliberate outrage amongst a &lsquo;&rsquo;substantial number&rsquo;&rsquo; of the followers of that religion. But this definition is so vague it&rsquo;s hard to imagine how the legislation can be put into effect. What is a substantial number? Is it 99% &nbsp;of the followers of the religion in question? Or is one third of them enough? But couldn&rsquo;t the writers of Father Ted, Arthur Mathews and Graham Linehan, be accused of blasphemy?</p>\n<p>The main religious belief held by the &lsquo;&rsquo;Church of Dermotology&rsquo;&rsquo; is that God sent Dermot Ahern to Ireland to save the country from &lsquo;reasonable thinking.&rsquo; Underwear with the Church&rsquo;s symbol (the Star of Dermot) has even been made available for purchase! It is firmly believed that &nbsp;these &lsquo;magical&rsquo; underpants are protection against fire and bullets! It&rsquo;s also believed that ice-cream wafers are literally the body of Dermot Ahern. Therefore, anyone who eats ice-cream wafers is committing blasphemy against the followers of &nbsp;&lsquo;&rsquo;The Church of Dermotology.&rsquo;&rsquo; As well as this, the Church believes that it is hugely blasphemous to publish images of their God, Dermot Ahern, and they are willing to convict anyone who does so in order to test the law. A load of nonsense? Maybe so, but the organisation must be given credit for effectively raising attention to the seriousness of this legislation.</p>\n<p>We have to consider the implications this law has on other countries across the world. It &nbsp;seems the Irish blasphemy law is in fact fuelling international extremism. At the United Nations, Pakistan have already used Ireland&rsquo;s example to support the implementation of a similar legislation on an international level.</p>\n<p>In Ireland, there&rsquo;s a danger that the blasphemy law will encourage radicals to take extremist stances. Should programmes such as That&rsquo;s All We&rsquo;ve Time For and The Savage Eye watch their backs? Or will script writers for soaps have to avoid controversial subjects that condemn the Church? But then again, why would anyone be criticizing the Church&hellip;</p>\n<p>The idea of a law against blasphemy isn&lsquo;t a brand new concept &ndash; it was a part of &nbsp;Bunreacht na h&Eacute;ireann in 1937. Since then, however, attitudes in Ireland have totally changed. It seems ironic that this blasphemy law was written during the same year in which the scandals and horrors of the Catholic Church came to light. Of course, we can&rsquo;t deny that the Catholic Church had dominance over the State when the Constitution was first written. But times have changed. This legislation threatens our freedom of speech. Will we accept such a law in the pluralist society of Ireland today?</p>", "Imageurl": "<p>An Eaglais is consp&oacute;id&iacute; in &Eacute;irinn i l&aacute;thair na huaire n&aacute; &ldquo;The Church of Dermotology.&rdquo; (N&oacute; an dara Eaglais is consp&oacute;id&iacute; ar a laghad.) Cheapf&aacute; gur cultas reiligi&uacute;nach eile at&aacute; ann ar dt&uacute;s. N&oacute; gr&iacute;os cnis! Ach n&iacute; mar sin at&aacute; an sc&eacute;al&hellip;</p>\n<p>Buna&iacute;odh &ldquo;The Church of Dermotology&rdquo; mar fhreagra ar an dl&iacute; nua in &eacute;adan an diamhasla a th&aacute;inig i bhfeidhm ar an gc&eacute;ad l&aacute; d&rsquo;&Eacute;an&aacute;ir 2010 mar chuid den Ac